issue.title: Wrong containers deployed and random image name after stack deployment
issue.body:
### Before you start please confirm the following.

- [X] Yes, I've searched similar issues on [GitHub](https://github.com/portainer/portainer/issues).
- [X] Yes, I've checked whether this issue is covered in the Portainer [documentation](https://docs.portainer.io) or [knowledge base](https://portal.portainer.io/knowledge).

### Problem Description

I have a very strange case which has been bugging my mind for quite some time now.

- I have two contains running on through a portainer managed stack.
- One of the containers exist quickly when stopped, the other takes a bit longer.
- When i update the stack by updating the tags of the containers, i see the following happening
1. Two new containers are created with the name of the container, prepended with a random string.
2. The fast exiting contains stops
3. In the same millisecond, the newly created container is renamed to have the new name, but is still in the created phase. The other new container still has the random string in front of it.
4. The slowly stopping container stops, and the other container is renamed to have the new name. At this point, everything looks perfect and in the running stated
5. The image name of the slowly stopped container is renamed to a random string which is not similar to once i have seen before.
- On inspecting the random named image, i see the tag still is a reference to the OLD image. (so the one which was stopped) and the new image is not present.

Some notes:
I am going back in the semver version, so e.g. 0.5.4 to 0.5.3.
I am calling the update portainer from the API (PUT /stacks/{id} with prune=true)
Portainer version 2.18.4

This seems to be happening reproducable but not in always
As you can imagine, its quite troublesome if the old container keeps running while i dont expect so and get a 200 back. Please let me know if there is more info i can provide. 

### Expected Behavior

The stack is deployed with the right versions, and the image tag is not some random string. OR an error response from portainer that the stack couldn't be deployed.

### Actual Behavior

Stack gets deployed with a wrong container and weird image name

### Steps to Reproduce

1. Having two containers
- One that stops quickly
- One that stops slowly. Set the timeout to be great so it will not be killed.
4. Update the tags of the containers to go down in semver.
5. See that the image name is now a random set of characters.

### Portainer logs or screenshots

_No response_

### Portainer version

2.19.1

### Portainer Edition

Community Edition (CE)

### Platform and Version

Docker 24.0.2

### OS and Architecture

Ubuntu 22.04

### Browser

Firefox 118.0.2

### What command did you use to deploy Portainer?

```bash
API (PUT /stacks/{id} with prune=true)
```


### Additional Information

_No response_

comment.body:
Update: We've found the reason why the containers were wrongly deployed and it's not a portainer issue. For future reference, the image tag becoming random characters was discussed here https://portainer.slack.com/archives/C2AGKR5JB/p1698116159546239?thread_ts=1697589715.471959&cid=C2AGKR5JB. In short
`The image name changing to random characters is because you've pulled a newer version of that image and tag than what the container itself is running. Because you've pulled a new version, the previous image and tag combination is no longer accurate for that running container.`
With this information this issue can be closed
